			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2023</a> paper:</span><br><i>Temporal Breakpoints for Multiverse Debugging</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MatthiasPasquier.html">Matthias Pasquier</a>, <a href="../profile/CiprianTeodorov.html">Ciprian Teodorov</a>, <a href="../profile/FrédéricJouault.html">Frédéric Jouault</a>, <a href="../profile/MatthiasBrun.html">Matthias Brun</a>, <a href="../profile/LukaLeRoux.html">Luka Le Roux</a>, <a href="../profile/LoïcLagadec.html">Loïc Lagadec</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3623476.3623526">10.1145/3623476.3623526</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagM">T5C: Testing</span></a><ul><li> The paper extends multiverse debugging with temporal breakpoints, advancing debugging/testing support for exploring executions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> Breakpoints are defined over runtime execution traces of nondeterministic/concurrent programs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5g.html"><span class="tagL">T5G: Traceability</span></a><ul><li> Temporal breakpoints rely on richer temporal properties over execution histories, strengthening trace-based reasoning.
</li></ul></li></ul>
